article.description: Zach Randolph had 21 points and nine rebounds to help the Trail Blazers snap a four-game losing streak with a 91-83 victory over the Bobcats on Monday night in a matchup of the last-place teams in each conference.

related.description: Theo Ratliff missed the Trail Blazers' game against the Bobcats because of a sprained left knee.

related.title: Sprained knee sidelines Blazers' Ratliff vs. Bobcats
related.headline: Sprained knee sidelines Blazers' Ratliff vs. Bobcats

article.headline: Randolph helps Blazers end four-game skid
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Charlotte Bobcats coach Bernie Bickerstaff sounded embarassed after his team's poor showing against the Portland Trail Blazers. The Trail Blazers entered the contest having lost their past three games by 33, 32 and 32 points respectively, but shot 46 percent against Charlotte in a 91-83 victory on Monday night. Zach Randolph had 21 points and nine rebounds to help the Trail Blazers snap a four-game losing streak overall in a matchup of the last-place teams in each conference. "The bottom line is whether we were prepared and ready to play when they threw the ball up," Bickerstaff said. "It didn't appear that way to me and I think that's a responsibility that when people come to the arena and pay their hard-earned cash to watch you perform, then you owe them a performance. And that's effort. And damn if we gave effort tonight. "And that is not speaking of the collective group, but there were players who did not have effort and that's inexcusable." Bickerstaff sent that same message to his players in the locker room after the game. "He's right, our effort was horrible," point guard Brevin Knight said. "[Portland] had come out the last three games and lost by 30 points on average and they come in here today and kick our butts from beginning to end. It's embarrassing. Bernie is right in everything he said. The effort we put forth can't be tolerated at any level. And there is no excuse for how we played." Darius Miles, playing in his first game since Dec. 4, gave the Trail Blazers a boost on offense with 14 points, while Juan Dixon scored all 12 of his points in the first half. Miles had been sidelined with a sprained left knee. Portland had expected to hold Miles out until after the All-Star break, but he was pressed into action due to a knee injury that sidelined starting center Theo Ratliff. "What I was hoping was by bringing in him would be that these guys would be excited to see him and we could get a lift -- and I think they were," Portland coach Nate McMillan said. "He came in and did some pretty good things. He made some nice shots and ran some pick and rolls. We needed to have a change and he was a change. I think the guys responded to him returning tonight." Added Randolph: "We had to bounce back. Our guys came out and played hard. D-Miles came back and we just came out and played hard." Randolph scored 10 points in the fourth quarter and put the game away with an impressive scoring flurry in the final five minutes. With Portland nursing a five-point lead, Randolph hit a short jumper, added a free throw and then drew a foul on a dunk with 2:21 left in the game on a pretty pass from Sebastian Telfair. That play put the Blazers up by nine and ended any comeback hopes for the Bobcats. At one point, Portland led by as many as 13 in the second quarter. "They came in a rut and we should have kept them in that rut," Knight said. "We should have taken their hearts right there. We didn't do that. We let them get a good feeling like they could win. ... In this game you let someone get on a roll they can beat you. That's what happened. They deservedly beat us and manhandled us." Raymond Felton returned to the starting lineup after missing one game with a leg injury and led Charlotte with 16 points, while Knight, Bernard Robinson and Primo Brezec each had 14. Despite playing without emotion, the Bobcats managed to make it a game after battling back from a 12-point deficit in the third quarter with a 13-0 run. Six of those points came on dunks in transition. But Charlotte seemed to tire down the stretch with a handful of turnovers. Bickerstaff felt like his team took the Trail Blazers lightly right from the opening tip. "That was an opportunity we didn't seize," Bickerstaff said. "It's a situation where it looks and appears as though as we took it for granted and there's no way we can conceivably do that. ... That was the kind of performance it was -- it was awful."

Game notes
The Bobcats were without backup center Jake Voskuhl, who is likely to miss the next two games with the flu. The Bobcats are already without big men Emeka Okafor, Sean May and Gerald Wallace. ... Felton banked in a shot from beyond midcourt at the end of the first quarter.
